<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a rhumb line?", answer: "A rhumb line, also called a loxodrome, is a path on the surface of the Earth that crosses every meridian at the same angle. In other words, it is a line of constant compass bearing. Unlike a great circle, which is the shortest path between two points, a rhumb line is generally longer but far easier to navigate because the compass heading never changes. On a Mercator projection map, rhumb lines appear as straight lines, which is one of the main reasons Mercator maps have been used for navigation for centuries." },
  { question: "How does a rhumb line differ from a great circle?", answer: "A great circle is the shortest distance between two points on a sphere; a rhumb line is a path of constant bearing. For short distances, the two are nearly identical. For long distances, especially over high latitudes, they can differ significantly. A great circle between New York and London arcs northward over Iceland and Greenland, while the rhumb line goes more or less straight east and is about 3 percent longer. Airlines and modern ships follow great circles to save fuel, but older navigation methods and small vessels often use rhumb lines for their simplicity." },
  { question: "When should I use rhumb lines?", answer: "Rhumb lines are the right choice any time constant bearing matters more than shortest distance: small-craft sailing in calm waters, land surveying, simple autopilot routes, drawing straight lines on a Mercator map, or any situation where you cannot easily change heading during the journey. Traditional marine navigation used rhumb lines almost exclusively, plotting them with parallel rulers on a Mercator chart, because a constant compass course was far more practical before GPS and electronic navigation." },
  { question: "Why does rhumb line distance differ from straight line on a globe?", answer: "On a globe, a rhumb line spirals slightly toward the pole unless it runs exactly east-west or north-south. That spiral makes it longer than the corresponding great circle. On a Mercator map, the rhumb line looks straight because Mercator projection stretches distances near the poles in a way that exactly compensates for the spiral, preserving bearings but distorting areas and distances." },
  { question: "What happens at the equator and along meridians?", answer: "Along the equator, a rhumb line and a great circle are identical, because the equator is itself both a great circle and a line of constant easting. Along a meridian (a north-south line), the two are also identical. The biggest differences between rhumb lines and great circles occur on long east-west routes at high latitudes, where the spherical geometry curves most aggressively." }
]) %>

